faqs:
  - q: "When is a French Bulldog considered senior?"
    a: "Frenchies are a smaller breed but a relatively short-lived one (typically 10–12 years), so they cross into 'senior' around 8–9 years — earlier than a Dachshund or Yorkie of similar size. Don't wait for a number: watch for a greying muzzle, slower walks, more time sleeping, stiffer mornings, and — uniquely for this breed — any worsening of the breathing (more snoring, noisier panting, tiring faster on warm days). A Frenchie's lifelong issues don't retire in old age: the gut-skin sensitivity, the flatulence and above all the brachycephalic (flat-faced) airway are all still there, and the senior dietary shift layers fewer calories, more joint support and softer textures on top of the limited-ingredient brief you've always followed."
  - q: "How much should I feed a senior French Bulldog per day?"
    a: "Less than you fed them as a young adult — and for this breed, weight is a breathing issue, not just a waistline one. An adult Frenchie (8–14kg) eats roughly 120–200g of dry food a day; a steadier, less active senior needs fewer calories than that, even though the breed gains weight easily. As a rough June-2026 guide, feeding an 11kg senior as its sole diet costs about £0.50–0.85/day on quality grain-free kibble, £0.80–1.10/day air-dried, or £1.20–2.00/day on fresh-cooked subscription. The honest method is to weigh meals on a kitchen scale, weigh your dog monthly, and keep the ribs easily felt — every excess gram crowds an already-compromised airway and reduces heat tolerance."
  - q: "What should I look for in food for an older French Bulldog?"
    a: "Five things, the first two carried straight from the breed's lifelong brief and now more important than ever: tight calorie control (excess weight directly worsens brachycephalic breathing and overheating, and a senior burns fewer calories than the adult it was); and a limited-ingredient, gut-gentle recipe (grain-free, single named protein, prebiotics) to calm the flatulence and the skin-fold flare-ups that food allergy drives. Then add the senior layer: joint support (glucosamine, chondroitin, omega-3 for ageing hips and the arthritis age brings); easy digestibility with high palatability — gently-cooked fresh, air-dried or cold-pressed recipes sit better on an ageing gut; and a small kibble size or soft, moisture-rich texture for the breed's short muzzle, undershot jaw and ageing teeth."
  - q: "Why does staying lean matter so much for a senior French Bulldog specifically?"
    a: "Because of the breathing. French Bulldogs are brachycephalic — the flat face means a narrowed airway, and many already live with some degree of brachycephalic obstructive airway syndrome (BOAS). Excess body fat presses on the chest and the soft tissues around an already-crowded throat, so an overweight Frenchie breathes harder, tires faster and overheats more easily — and in old age, when stamina and heat tolerance are already falling, that margin matters more. Weight is the one factor you fully control, and on this breed it's the most breathing-protective and heat-protective thing you can manage. It's mostly done at the food bowl, not the vet."
  - q: "My senior Frenchie still has terrible wind and itchy skin — can food help?"
    a: "Yes, and it's worth getting right, because both the gas and the skin-fold dermatitis often trace back to diet. Frenchies are flatulence champions — partly because they gulp air through that flat face (aerophagia), partly because poor-quality, hard-to-digest food ferments in the gut. A highly digestible, limited-ingredient, grain-free recipe with a single named protein and prebiotics reduces both the fermentation and the food-allergy load that inflames the skin folds. Settle the gut and you often settle the skin. Feed from a slow/flat bowl to cut the air-gulping, transition foods slowly, and see your vet if itching, ear trouble or runny stools persist — food is one lever, not the only one."
  - q: "Should I switch my senior French Bulldog to a 'senior' labelled food?"
    a: "Not automatically — the 'senior' label isn't regulated and quality varies hugely. What matters is the profile: moderate calories and fat to keep weight off the airway, a limited-ingredient grain-free base for the sensitive gut and skin, joint support, adequate named protein for muscle, easy digestibility and a small or soft format the short muzzle can manage. A high-quality fresh, air-dried or grain-free adult food that hits those marks can beat a mediocre 'senior' recipe. Whatever you choose, transition gradually over 7–10 days — a sudden change is a fast route to a Frenchie gut upset."
  - q: "How do I stop my senior French Bulldog overheating?"
    a: "Manage the weight first — it's the single biggest food-related lever. An overweight Frenchie has less airway room and worse heat tolerance, a dangerous combination in a flat-faced senior whose stamina is already fading. Keep the dog lean (ribs easily felt), weigh every meal, count treats inside the daily total, and favour moderate-fat recipes. Beyond the bowl: avoid exercise in the heat of the day, never leave a Frenchie in a warm car or conservatory, provide shade and water, and treat heavy panting that won't settle as an emergency. Subscription brands that portion automatically to a maintenance or weight-loss goal (Years, Butternut Box, tails.com) make keeping a food-motivated Frenchie lean far easier."
